nts among the poem's several versions. This record of Stein's multi-layered revisions enables readers to engage more fully with the author's radically experimental poem and also to detect the literary impact of Stein's relationship with Toklas. The editors’ preface and poet Joan Retallack’s introduction offer insight into the complexities of reading Stein's poetry and the innovative modes of reading that her works require and generate. Students and admirers of Stein will welcome this illuminating new contribution to Stein’s oeuvre.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAmerican literaturey20th century. 7aPOETRY / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAshbery, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHollister, Susannah, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aRetallack, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSetina, Emily, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSutherland, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030015309540uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015733840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300157338423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300157338/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY